 x \\\\ y \\end{pmatrix}\\). The orthogonality condition gives us:\n\\[\n1 \\cdot x + 2 \\cdot y = 0 \\implies x + 2y = 0 \\implies x = -2y.\n\\]\nNext, we know that \\(\\mathbf{a} + \\mathbf{b} = \\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\\\ 7 \\end{pmatrix}\\). Since \\(\\mathbf{a}\\) is parallel to \\(\\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\ 2 \\end{pmatrix}\\), we can write \\(\\mathbf{a} = k \\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\\\ 2 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} k \\\\ 2k \\end{pmatrix}\\) for some scalar \\(k\\). Therefore, we have:\n\\[\n\\begin{pmatrix} k \\\\ 2k \\end{pmatrix} + \\begin{pmatrix} x \\\\ y \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\\\ 7 \\end{pmatrix}.\n\\]\nSubstituting \\(x = -2y\\) into the equation, we get:\n\\[\n\\begin{pmatrix} k \\\\ 2k \\end{pmatrix} + \\begin{pmatrix} -2y \\\\ y \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\\\ 7 \\end{pmatrix} \\implies \\begin{pmatrix} k - 2y \\\\ 2k + y \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\\\ 7 \\end{pmatrix}.\n\\]\nThis gives us the system of equations:\n\\[\nk - 2y = 4,\n\\]\n\\[\n2k + y = 7.\n\\]\nWe can solve this system by first solving the first equation for \\(k\\):\n\\[\nk = 4 + 2y.\n\\]\nSubstituting \\(k = 4 + 2y\\) into the second equation, we get:\n\\[\n2(4 + 2y) + y = 7 \\implies 8 + 4y + y = 7 \\implies 8 + 5y = 7 \\implies 5y = -1 \\implies y = -\\frac{1}{5}.\n\\]\nNow, substituting \\(y = -\\frac{1}{5}\\) back into the equation \\(k = 4 + 2y\\), we get:\n\\[\nk = 4 + 2\\left(-\\frac{1}{5}\\right) = 4 - \\frac{2}{5} = \\frac{20}{5} - \\frac{2}{5} = \\frac{18}{5}.\n\\]\nThus, the vector \\(\\mathbf{b}\\) is:\n\\[\n\\mathbf{b} = \\begin{pmatrix} x \\\\ y \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} -2y \\\\ y \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} -2\\left(-\\frac{1}{5}\\right) \\\\ -\\frac{1}{5} \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} \\frac{2}{5} \\\\ -\\frac{1}{5} \\end{pmatrix}.\n\\]\nTherefore, the answer is:\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\begin{pmatrix} \\frac{2}{5} \\\\ -\\frac{1}{5} \\end{pmatrix}}.\n\\]", "truth": "\\begin{pmatrix} 2/5 \\\\ -1/5 \\end{pmatrix}", "reward_form